"mesh:D006528"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HCC", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9996727705001831, "span": {"begin": 892, "end": 895}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016604"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AFB1", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9907983541488647, "span": {"begin": 927, "end": 931}}, {"id": ["mesh:C026209"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oltipraz", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999035120010376, "span": {"begin": 959, "end": 967}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9850685000419617, "span": {"begin": 1086, "end": 1092}}, {"id": ["mesh:C007020"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "chlorophyllin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994686245918274, "span": {"begin": 1125, "end": 1138}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016604"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AFB1", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990076422691345, "span": {"begin": 1186, "end": 1190}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016604"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AFB1", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984211921691895, "span": {"begin": 1253, "end": 1257}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9998111128807068, "span": {"begin": 1315, "end": 1320}}], "text": "Formation of AFB1-induced DNA adducts clearly precede tumor formation, thus the necessary temporal pattern exists. The plethora of published chemoprevention studies support a relationship between AFB1-induced DNA adducts and hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). There are some evaluations that claim (Bechtel et al. 1989) linearity in the dose-response for adduct formation as a function of dose in both rats and trout;  but linearity does not seem to apply, however, for adducts and HCC. Recent work of Johnson et al. (2014) showed that HCC incidence was reduced to zero by the chemoprotectant CDDO-Im, while around 30% of the original level of N7-AFB1-G adducts were still present. These authors note that there remained ~15,000 adducts per cell after application of the chemoprotectant, while no HCC tumors were induced.  Other chemoprevention data also support the reduction or elimination of HCC, accompanied by a reduction in AFB1-induced DNA adducts, e.g., oltipraz (Kensler et al.,1987&#160;; Roebuck et al., 1991; Maxuitenko et al., 1993).  There are also chemoprevention data from humans demonstrating administration of chlorophyllin results in an increased elimination of urinary AFB1-induced adducts, presumably stemming from a reduced burden of AFB1-induced adducts, and an assumed concomitant reduction in tumor burden (Jubert et al., 2009) (see Chemoprevention section).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:41:08 +0000 2026"}